<body lang=3DEN-US link=3Dblue vlink=3Dpurple style=3D'tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=3DSection1>

<p class=3DMsoTitle><a name=3D"_top"></a>A Welding Data Dictionary</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h1><a name=3D"_Toc68316833">Abstract</a></h1>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>This data dictionary specifies data elements that are =
used
to describe the design, fabrication and inspection of weldments.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>It comprises welding information f=
rom
several authoritative sources.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </spa=
n>Data
include description of component materials, details of joints and welds, and
variables of the welding processes.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>The data dictionary provides, in one document, the welding informati=
on
needed to develop format specifications for digital data that can be exchan=
ged
by computer programs.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span></p>

<h1><a name=3D"_Toc68316834">Keywords</a></h1>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span class=3DGramE><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-famil=
y:Arial'>data</span></span><span
style=3D'mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'> dictionary, digital welding data, weld
inspection results, welding procedure specification, welding terms, weldment
design.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'><o:p>&nbsp;=
</o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h1><a name=3D"_Toc68316835">Foreword</a></h1>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>In 1992, welding information formats were described in=
 two
American Welding Society (AWS) specifications, <i>AWS A9.1- Standard Guide =
for
Describing Arc Welds in Computerized Material Property and Nondestructive
Examination Databases</i>, and <i>AWS A9.2 - Standard Guide for Recording A=
rc
Weld Material Property and Nondestructive Examination Data in Computerized
Databases</i>.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>This document
expands the scope of those documents and could serve as a core document if =
an
AWS committee undertakes a new specification project.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Current individual AWS
specifications are rich in terms and data items describing materials, design
and processes.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>This data dict=
ionary
gathers the information in a single document, to be used by data modelers w=
ith
specific encoding formats in mind.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Examples of format specifications are STEP and XML.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The ultimate purpose is to facilit=
ate
exchange of welding data between application software programs developed by
different vendors.</p>

<b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style=3D'font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman";
color:black;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-lan=
guage:
AR-SA'><br clear=3Dall style=3D'page-break-before:always'>
</span></b>

<h1 align=3Dcenter style=3D'text-align:center'><a name=3D"_Toc68316836">TAB=
LE OF
CONTENTS</a></h1>

<b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style=3D'font-size:12.0pt;

on-break'>

<div class=3DSection3>

<h4>A Welding Data Dictionary</h4>

<h1><a name=3D"_Toc68316837">Scope</a></h1>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:non=
e'>This
document includes data describing design of welded products, design of
weldments including detailed weld and joint description, arc welding process
specification, and destructive weld inspection.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Common welding documents that
convey this information are welding procedure specifications (WPSs) and
mechanical testing reports.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>T=
hese
documents are often implemented using hard copy or simple, but non-standard
data formats.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Variables of ot=
her
welding processes such as gas and laser welding have not been covered at th=
is
time.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span style=3D'fo=
nt-family:
Arial'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:non=
e'><span
style=3D'font-family:Arial'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:non=
e'>Some
of the variables and data types needed in standard welding procedure
specifications (SWPSs<span class=3DGramE>) <span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;</span>and</span> procedure qualification
records (PQRs) are not addressed.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nb=
sp;
</span>Examples are ranges of allowed values (e.g., minimum and maximum all=
owed
current), conditions that are expressly not allowed, conditions that are
optional, or multiple conditions that are allowed.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>These should be straightforw=
ard
extensions of the data elements and types already defined.<span
style=3D'font-family:Arial'> <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:non=
e'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:non=
e'>Also
not addressed are overall formats for standard forms or standard test result
reports.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>These are left to da=
ta
modelers according to the requirements of their customers.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Appendix 1 lists many other =
items
that are not included in this document.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nb=
sp;
</span>They are suggestions to committees of experts who could expand the d=
ocument&#8217;s
scope. </p>

<h1 style=3D'margin-top:12.0pt'><a name=3D"_Toc68316838">Purpose</a></h1>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>A data dictionary is the starting point for developing
specifications for data formats for digital welding data.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>It gathers relevant data in one pl=
ace,
establishes standard labels and descriptions of the items, and designates d=
ata
types to them.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The purpose of=
 a
standard data format is to enable independent computer programs (applicatio=
ns)
to exchange information with minimal or no cost and effort. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>This document&#8217;s form is suitable for a formal st=
andard
to be used by many different manufacturing industries that use welding.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The existence of a single data
dictionary as source for data modeling will ease the challenge of gathering=
 the
welding knowledge, and make implementations of different formats more
consistent.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Examp=
le
formats are STEP and XML.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Consistency eases the challenge of converting between the differing =
formats
should it be necessary.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Easy
conversion between formats makes the decision of which format to use less
critical.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>When da=
ta
modelers discover improvements to the model the changes can be reflected in=
 the
high level data dictionary as well as to the implementation being worked on=
 at
the time.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>This way other
implementations can benefit from the improvement.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>It is envisioned that welding standards documents that
contain forms will use this data model to build their own structures to
represent the form information.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>This will enable encoding <span class=3DGramE>of<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>the</span> information in a standa=
rd
format so it may be conveyed electronically and not be limited to hardcopy =
or
proprietary formats. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>The data dictionary is written in English rather than a
formal modeling language so that:</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:21.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;mso-lis=
t:l3 level1 lfo5;
tab-stops:list 21.0pt'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'=
>-<span
style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=
&nbsp;
</span></span><![endif]><span class=3DGramE>welding</span> experts can unde=
rstand
the information and work on it to improve it without learning a computer
language.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:21.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;mso-lis=
t:l3 level1 lfo5;
tab-stops:list 21.0pt'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'=
>-<span
style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=
&nbsp;
</span></span><![endif]><span class=3DGramE>it</span> can serve as the comm=
on
ground between welding experts and the data modelers who will develop detai=
led
specifications.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:21.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;mso-lis=
t:l3 level1 lfo5;
tab-stops:list 21.0pt'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'=
>-<span
style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=
&nbsp;
</span></span><![endif]><span class=3DGramE>it</span> is not biased toward =
any
particular encoding scheme.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>This dictionary goes beyond presenting all elementary
information units as a flat list.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>It suggests gathering of elements into frequently used groupings.<sp=
an
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>These groupings are not rigid: data
modelers or refiners of the data dictionary can ungroup or regroup as they =
see
fit.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The groupings present the
information in recognizable units that make understanding the document easi=
er.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>This data dictionary is not sufficient to specify the =
design
of a database or of a complete specification for standard data.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Its terms and type definitions are=
 the
building blocks that need to be supplemented by encoding rules, and
relationships like those described in database tables.</p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316839">Source Documents</a></h2>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>These documents contain definitions of the variables, =
or
state the need for variables in report documents to describe welding produc=
ts,
processes or inspection results. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:39.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;mso-lis=
t:l4 level1 lfo4;
tab-stops:list 39.0pt'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-we=
ight:
bold'><span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>1.<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times Ne=
w Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>AASHTO/AWS D1.5M/D1.5:2002 &#8211; <i>Bridge
Welding Code</i>. <b><o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316840">Guidelines Used in Building the Data Dictionar=
y</a></h2>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>The primary audience for this document is do=
main
experts in welding.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>They must=
 be
able to understand its content and be able to refine and expand it, without
needing computer programming experience.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&n=
bsp;
</span>The document then becomes a bridge between them and computer experts,
who will encode the data and manipulate it in computer programs that serve =
the
welding experts.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>The item descriptions in this document should
not be cited as formal definitions of terms.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The descriptions are original, or =
are
shortened or paraphrased versions of formal definitions.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The source documents, usually AWS =
in
origin<span class=3DGramE>,<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>s=
hould</span>
be used. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Sources of most definitions are AWS
documents.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>When values are shown as &#8220;enumeration =
of:<span
class=3DGramE>&#8221;,</span> this means that only the listed values are
allowed.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>This is a restrictio=
n on
the allowed values for the element. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>This data dictionary specifies, for some
elements, hierarchical relationships of sub-elements, and enumerated
values.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Element grouping and
enumeration are constraints on how the data can be used in a computer progr=
am
or in a digital file.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The
constraints promote increased consistency between different vendors&#8217;
implementations of products or of digital format specifications.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>The element naming convention <span class=3D=
GramE>of<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>lower</span> case words separated =
by
underscores was chosen to be human readable, and mildly suggesting future t=
ags
to be used in formal encoding.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>The convention is not intended to suggest a preference of one encodi=
ng
method over another. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Some provisions are made for specifying units
for measured variables, especially to distinguish between <st1:country-regi=
on><st1:place>U.S.</st1:place></st1:country-region>
customary, or &#8220;inch-pound&#8221;<span class=3DGramE>,<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>and</span> International System of=
 Units
(SI) usage.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>More examination =
of the
need and suggestions for values are needed from welding experts. </p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316841">Sections of this Document</a></h2>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><b><i>Weld Design Data</i></b> describes the desired w=
eld
that joins two workpieces.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>It
includes descriptions of the workpieces (e.g., thickness, material), the
geometric relationship between the workpieces (e.g., tee, butt), the edge s=
hapes
of the workpieces to form a joint, and the desired properties of the weld, =
such
as size and degree of penetration.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>There are usually seve=
ral
different ways to produce a designed weld, e.g., by varying <b><i>Welding
Process Data </i></b><span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;</span>such as
welding process, number of passes, thickness of consumable, gas composition,
etc.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span><b><i>Testing and Inspec=
tion
Data</i></b> is information gathered by measuring characteristics of the we=
ld
after it is made, usually to compare to the design data.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>The appendices contain next-step information for data
modelers, some high level background on the concept of standard data formats
for welding, and suggestions for expansion of the scope of the next version=
 of
this data dictionary. </p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316842">Dictionary Field Definitions</a></h2>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>There are two kinds of dictionary entries,
&#8220;element&#8221; and &#8220;type&#8221;.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Types are data templates that are =
reused
in multiple elements.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>T=
he
prefix &#8220;p:&#8221; means primitive, one of Boolean, string, integer or
decimal.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>An element is a
unique chunk of information used in describing welding.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The distinction between type=
s and
elements will be further refined in detailed data modeling &#8211; the major
criterion is to make the model concise and understandable. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Diagram - When an element has subelements, a
sketch of its sub-elements is shown to aid understanding.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Diagrams show only one level=
 of
decomposition.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Appendix 4 con=
tains
a few selected diagrams of multilevel diagrams.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>In the diagrams, the 3 short=
 bars
in some boxes is an artifact of the documentation tool and <span class=3DGr=
amE>is</span>
not relevant.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The small=
 arrow
in the lower left corner indicates that the element is defined globally, i.=
e.
it is independent of the element definition it appears in. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Type &#8211; enumeration is used when there =
is
one choice from a list of simple values.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&n=
bsp;
</span><i>Choice of</i> is used when there are several non-simple elements,=
 one
of which must be picked. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Values &#8211; this field appears only for
enumerated types, showing the allowed values.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Children &#8211; list of elements that are p=
arts
of this element. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Used by &#8211; the name of elements that
contain this element. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Source &#8211; citation of a standard or
industry handbook that lists the need for the information.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>When the source for a sub-el=
ement
is the same as its parent element, the source information is not repeated. =
</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Description &#8211; prose description, or
standard definition if one exists, to allow data modelers to select the
appropriate elements for specific applications, forms and reports.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>It is an important task of w=
elding
experts, not data modelers, to develop precise descriptions.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.75in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list=
:l6 level1 lfo3;
tab-stops:list .75in'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-family:Symbo=
l;
mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>&middot;<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roma=
n"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]>Underlined type and element names are links =
that
can be used in electronic documents for easy jumping to definitions. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>The index below is included for use in electronic docu=
ments
that can use the links to the definitions.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The types and elements are
arranged in alphabetic order in each section.</p>

  12.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman";color:bla=

  alloy added in making a ... joint&quot;.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316878"></a><a name=3DLink01C0CA18></a><span class=3DG=
ramE><span
style=3D'mso-bookmark:_Toc68316878'>2.20<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&n=
bsp;
</span></span><span style=3D'mso-bookmark:_Toc68316878'><span style=3D'font=
-weight:
normal'>element</span></span></span><span style=3D'mso-bookmark:_Toc6831687=

<h1><a name=3D"_Toc68316880">3.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Testing and Inspection Data</a></h1>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>Terms typically used in inspection applications that a=
lready
appear in the previous sections will not be duplicated in this section.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The scope is data that is
essential to reporting results of tests.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&n=
bsp;
</span>In addition, some fields were added that are found on test results f=
orms
that are essential for record keeping and for tracing the source of results=
.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Example data are testing machine t=
ype,
model and serial number, technician running the test, and date of test.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'page-break-after:avoid'>The scope of this data
dictionary addresses mechanical testing, but not non-destructive (e.g., Wel=
ding
Handbook, Vol. 1, p. 213), metallurgical or compositional testing. These ar=
eas
need to be documented for complete coverage of weld testing procedures and
their results.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-b=
idi-font-family:
"Times New Roman";color:black'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

    </td>
   </tr>
  </table>
  <p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'page-break-after:avoid'><span style=3D'font=

  10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-bidi-font-family:"=
Times New Roman";
  color:black'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style=3D'mso-yfti-lastrow:yes'>
  <td width=3D103 valign=3Dtop style=3D'width:61.5pt;border:solid gray 1.0p=

  <p class=3DMsoNormal align=3Dright style=3D'text-align:right'><span

  </td>

  of SI or U.S. Customary units celsius or fahrenheit.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>

<h1><a name=3D"_Toc68316917">Acknowledgments</a></h1>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>The technical information came primarily from American
Welding Society documents that were generated by hundreds of experts in div=
erse
fields.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>This document is an
extension of two 1992 AWS documents, &#8220;A9.1&#8221; and &#8220;A9.2&#82=
21;
that were written by the AWS A9 committee then chaired by Jerry E. Jones.<s=
pan
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Tom Siewert has for some tim=
e encouraged
the pursuit of a standard data specification for welding data.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Tim Quinn had extensive tech=
nical
input to this document.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Chris=
topher
Pepper helped edit the document. </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h1><a name=3D"_Toc68316918">Appendices</a></h1>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316919">Appendix 1 &#8211; Items to Add in Next Editio=
n of
Data Dictionary</a></h2>

<h3>Design</h3>

<ul style=3D'margin-top:0in' type=3Dsquare>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l0 level1 lfo9;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>three</span> dimensional geometric location of weld (inc=
luding
     weld begin, end points, contour), weld length.</li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l0 level1 lfo9;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>information</span> to describe the required accuracy of
     cutting of base materials (e.g., cutting, flame cutting, laser cutting=
),
     and accuracy of edge preparation, e.g., whether machining is required,=
 or
     if flame cutting is adequate.</li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l0 level1 lfo9;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>tubular</span> joints, e.g., Welding Handbook, Vol. 1, p=
. 174.
     </li>
</ul>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h3>Process</h3>

<ul style=3D'margin-top:0in' type=3Dsquare>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l7 level1 lfo8;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>items</span> needed to describe PQR or WPS ranges, minim=
um and
     maximum values, required processes (e.g., &#8220;preheat required&#822=
1;),
     prohibited status (e.g., &#8220;consumable inserts are not
     permitted&#8221;,<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>or opt=
ional
     conditions. </li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l7 level1 lfo8;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>non-arc</span> welding process details.</li>
</ul>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h3>Inspection</h3>

<ul style=3D'margin-top:0in' type=3Dsquare>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo7;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>crack</span> types from AWS 3.0 Figure 33, p. 83, and we=
ld
     discontinuities - Figure 32.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
     </span>These would be used in a visual inspection report. <span
     style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'><o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo7;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>welding</span> test positions from AWS 3.0 &#8211; Figur=
es 18
     and 19.<span style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'><o:p></o:p><=
/span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo7;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     class=3DGramE>non-destructive</span> examination (NDE)<span
     style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>parameters and results. <span
     style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'><o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo7;tab-stops:list .5in=
'>AWS
     D14.6, <i>Specification for Welding of Rotating Elements of Equipment,=
 </i>is
     a rich source of welding terms and variables that should eventually be
     covered.<i> </i><span style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'><o:=
p></o:p></span></li>
</ul>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>Note &#8211; AWS D14.6 </p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316920">Appendix 2 - Tasks for data modelers</a></h2>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>This data di=
ctionary
is not sufficiently rich to specify a data base design or a data format.<sp=
an
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Some of the tasks needed for detai=
led
design are listed below. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul style=3D'margin-top:0in' type=3Dsquare>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'>Strengthen
     relationships of data elements, i.e. grouping elements into reusable c=
hunks
     and choosing exact encodings of data types and their values (e.g., val=
ues
     for enumerated data).<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Th=
is
     will be the job of data modelers.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbs=
p;
     </span>They will test the data model for completeness by using scenari=
os
     of data flow from industrial welding facilities. <span style=3D'mso-bi=
di-font-size:
     10.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Harmonize the AWS data model with =
any
     that may be developed in specific industries.<span
     style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The &#8220;CIMSteel
     Integration Standard&#8221;, described at http://<a
     href=3D"http://www.cis2.org/">www.cis2.org</a>, and
     http://www.coa.gatech.edu/~aisc/ is an example. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Specify optional and required data=
 that
     is dependent on other data &#8211; e.g., if base metal is a tube, then
     &#8220;diameter&#8221; is required information.<span
     style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>For example, if the process is
     automatic GMAW, gas composition is required data and an electrode size=
 is
     incorrect data.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>For
     example, if &#8220;backing_used&#8221; is true, then there must be dat=
a in
     &#8220;backing_type&#8221; &#8211; if &#8220;backing_used&#8221; is fa=
lse,
     there cannot be data in the &#8220;backing_type&#8221; field. <o:p></o=
:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Allow users to deal easily and
     unambiguously with U.S. Customary and/or SI units, and also within eac=
h of
     these, a choice of multiple unit scales, e.g., for linear speed,
     inches/second or feet/minute. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Decide whether to specify enumerat=
ions
     or to allow free use of text fields.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&=
nbsp;
     </span>E.g., joint types could be a string field, or <span class=3DGra=
mE>an</span>
     single choice among enumerated values in the specification.</span><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'> <o:p></o:p></sp=
an></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Specify data types to handle e.g.,
     min/max values of variables in SWPSs and PQRs.<span
     style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Also specify actual ran=
ges
     that are legal or allowed if appropriate. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Modularize definitions for maximum=
 reuse
     in different report forms, and also to reduce the number of elements to
     aid understandability.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
     </span>For example, many fields from WPSs are used in mechanical test
     results forms in reporting the processes and weld design that produced=
 the
     weld. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Pick encoding options to allow ext=
ensibility
     of data, to allow for conditions not anticipated by the modelers, or to
     use data unique to a company or a proprietary process.<span
     style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>However users are encouraged =
to fit
     their applications within the guidelines of the data models as much as
     possible, minimizing their use of &#8220;other&#8221; data types. <o:p=
></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Fine tune definitions and rules for
     specific standard reports, e.g., mechanical testing results. <o:p></o:=
p></span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Eliminate duplicate items, in the
     interest of computational efficiency and understandability. <o:p></o:p=
></span></li>
</ul>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.25in'><span style=3D'mso-bidi-fo=
nt-size:
10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>If an effort=
 goes
forward to develop formal data schema, the modelers will cooperate with mem=
bers
of the various AWS committees that authored standards documents to ensure
correct interpretation of the data, use of familiar terms, and design of
comprehensive and unambiguous enumerations where appropriate. <o:p></o:p></=
span></p>

<ul style=3D'margin-top:0in' type=3Dsquare>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Add data elements that welding exp=
erts
     deem required, that are not specified in the AWS documents.<span
     style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>E.g., some companies record t=
he
     serial number of the testing machine used, and the name of the testing
     technician.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span><o:p></o:p><=
/span></li>
 <li class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-list:l1 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .5in=
'><span
     style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Pick default values from the enume=
rated
     choices (a very detailed decision). <o:p></o:p></span></li>
</ul>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:A=
rial'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316921">Appendix 3 &#8211; The BIG PICTURE of welding =
data
exchange</a></h2>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><i><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbs=
p;</o:p></span></i></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal align=3Dcenter style=3D'text-align:center'><!--[if gte=
 vml 1]><v:shape
 id=3D"_x0000_i1086" type=3D"#_x0000_t75" style=3D'width:5in;height:270pt' =
o:ole=3D""
 o:bordertopcolor=3D"this" o:borderleftcolor=3D"this" o:borderbottomcolor=
=3D"this"
 o:borderrightcolor=3D"this">
 <v:imagedata src=3D"WDDFinal1_files/image057.wmz" o:title=3D""/>
 <w:bordertop type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
 <w:borderleft type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
 <w:borderbottom type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
 <w:borderright type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img border=3D0 width=3D482 height=3D362
src=3D"WDDFinal1_files/image061.gif" v:shapes=3D"_x0000_i1086"><![endif]><!=
--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type=3D"Embed" ProgID=3D"PowerPoint.Slide.8" ShapeID=3D"_x000=
0_i1086"
  DrawAspect=3D"Content" ObjectID=3D"_1143375211">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]--></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal>Modularization of welding specifications (instead of
pursuing all these areas in a single effort) will speed progress in each
smaller area, and allow experts to contribute their knowledge in narrower a=
reas
more efficiently.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal align=3Dcenter style=3D'text-align:center'><!--[if gte=
 vml 1]><v:shape
 id=3D"_x0000_i1087" type=3D"#_x0000_t75" style=3D'width:5in;height:270pt' =
o:ole=3D""
 o:bordertopcolor=3D"this" o:borderleftcolor=3D"this" o:borderbottomcolor=
=3D"this"
 o:borderrightcolor=3D"this">
 <v:imagedata src=3D"WDDFinal1_files/image059.wmz" o:title=3D""/>
 <w:bordertop type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
 <w:borderleft type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
 <w:borderbottom type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
 <w:borderright type=3D"single" width=3D"4"/>
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img border=3D0 width=3D482 height=3D362
src=3D"WDDFinal1_files/image062.gif" v:shapes=3D"_x0000_i1087"><![endif]><!=
--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type=3D"Embed" ProgID=3D"PowerPoint.Slide.8" ShapeID=3D"_x000=
0_i1087"
  DrawAspect=3D"Content" ObjectID=3D"_1143375213">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]--><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Aria=
l'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span class=3DGramE><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:=
10.0pt;
font-family:Arial'>Many manufacturing industries share welding as a fabrica=
tion
process.</span></span><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:=
Arial'><span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>The data dictionary helps define w=
elding
variables centrally so the industries can &#8220;borrow&#8221; them, instea=
d of
each industry developing their own definitions.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The goal is to avoid develop=
ment
of different &#8220;dialects&#8221; of data formats that the welding indust=
ry
would have to accommodate. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:A=
rial'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h2><a name=3D"_Toc68316922">Appendix 4 &#8211; Terminology differences bet=
ween
ISO and AWS</a></h2>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:39.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;mso-lis=
t:l4 level2 lfo4;
tab-stops:list 39.0pt'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:Arial'><span style=3D'mso-list:Ig=
nore'>1.<span
style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </spa=
n></span></span><![endif]><span
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>ISO does not use the word
&#8220;flange&#8221; in describing joints.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>It uses &#8220;edges turned
up&#8221;. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:39.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;mso-lis=
t:l4 level2 lfo4;
tab-stops:list 39.0pt'><![if !supportLists]><span style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:Arial'><span style=3D'mso-list:Ig=
nore'>2.<span
style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </spa=
n></span></span><![endif]><span
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>ISO does not describe &#8220;g=
roove
welds&#8221;.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>It uses &#8220;=
butt
weld&#8221; hyphenated with the name of the groove type. <o:p></o:p></span>=
</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.=
0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman";color:gray'><o:p>&=
nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
